s Maps controls|Different controls]]\n* [[Maps examples/OpenLayers searchmarkers|Searching through markers]]\n* [[Maps examples/OpenLayers shapes|polygons, lines, rectangles and circles]]\n* [[Maps examples/OpenLayers polygons on hover|polygons on hover]]\n* [[Maps examples/OpenLayers custom base layers|Map with custom base layers]]\n* [[Maps examples/OpenLayers visited icon|Changing the marker icon on click]]\n* [[Maps examples/OpenLayers direct link|Direct link rather then a popup]]\n\n== Map editor ==\n\n* [[Special:MapEditor]]\n\n== Coordinates and geocoding ==\n\n* [[Maps examples/Coordinates|Coordinate conversion]]\n* [[Maps examples/Geocode|Geocode addresses]]\n\n== Geospatial functions ==\n\n* [[Maps examples/Distance|Distance conversion]]\n* [[Maps examples/Geodistance|Distance calculation]]\n* [[Maps examples/Finddestination|Destination calculation]]\n\n[[Category:Maps]]\n[[Category:Examples]] {{HIDE CAT PREFIX|Maps examples/}}','utf-8'),(175,'[[Category:Examples]]','utf-8'),(176,'[[Category:Examples]]\n{{HIDE CAT PREFIX|Demo:}}','utf-8'),(177,'{{Demo/Help}}\n[[Category:Examples]]','utf-8'),(178,'[[Category:Examples]]','utf-8'),(179,'[[Category:Examples]]','utf-8'),(180,'{{Example\n | description = Inline queries offer many different parameters to control printout statements. This help page demonstrates the usage of the different \'\'\'options to the link parameter\'\'\'.\n | topic = Queries\n | extensions = \n | keywords = inline queries;table output\n | other links = [[Help:Inline queries]]\n}}\n\n== Available settings ==\n\n=== all (default) ===\nSetting the parameter \"link\" to \"all\" means that the results, i.e. the requested pages as well as the requested printouts will be linked. This is the default setting.\n<pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |link=all\n |limit=5\n}}\n</pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |link=all\n |limit=5\n}}\n\nSince this is the default setting one does not explicitly have to state <code>link=all</code> in the query:\n<pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |limit=5\n}}\n</pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |limit=5\n}}\n\n=== none ===\nSetting the parameter \"link\" to \"none\" means that neither the results, i.e. the requested pages nor the requested printouts will be linked. \n<pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |link=none\n |limit=5\n}}\n</pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |link=none\n |limit=5\n}}\n\n=== subject ===\nSetting the parameter \"link\" to \"subject\" means that the results, i.e. the requested pages will be linked but not the requested printouts. \n<pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |link=subject\n |limit=5\n}}\n</pre>\n{{#ask:\n [[Category:City]]\n [[Located in::+]]\n |?Located in\n |?Population\n |link=subject\n |limit=5\n}}\n\n[[Category:Examples]]','utf-8'),(181,'{{SMW user TOC (ru)}}\n\n== Parser function <tt>#ask</tt> ==\nThe basic way of writing an inline query is to use the parser function <tt>#ask</tt>. The query string (See [[Help:Selecting pages|selecting pages]] for syntax) and any [[Help:Displaying information|printout statements]] are directly given as parameter, like in the following example:\n\n{{example|Using <tt>#ask</tt> function\n|<pre><nowiki>\n{{#ask: [[Category:City]] [[located in::Germany]] \n| ?population \n| ?area#km² = Size in km²\n}}</nowiki></pre>\n\nHere we query for all cities located in Germany, and two additional printout statements are used (a simple one and one with some extra settings). This displays the following result on a page:\n\n{{#ask: [[Category:City]] [[located in::Germany]] \n| ?population\n| ?area#km² = Size in km²\n}}\n}}\n\n\nIt is common to put the query as the first parameter behind <tt>#ask:</tt>. All other parameters are separated by <tt>|</tt>, just like for other [[meta:Help:Parser_function|parser functions]]. The exact formatting of the inline query is not essential, but it is good to use line breaks to make it more readable to other editors. As with all templates, one line per parameter, starting with the <tt>|</tt> is most accepted in practice.\n\nNote that all the arguments to the <tt>#ask:</tt> function are ignored by the page parsing, hence the above example does not add a category or a «located in» property annotation to this page. A few more things to note are:\n* The pipe \'<tt>|</tt>\' symbol is used to separate the conditions from the property to display.\n* The conditions for display are a single argument to the <tt>#ask</tt> function, so there are no \'<tt>|</tt>\' symbols between them.\n* White space and line breaks can be used within the <tt>#ask</tt> function, SMW is fairly flexible there.\n* The format of the results display changes when you request display of additional properties. SMW picks an appropriate default format for query results, but you also have detailed control of the appearance of query results.\n\nKnowing the basics of [[Help:Selecting pages|query string]] and [[Help:Displaying information|printout statements]] therefore is enough to write many kinds of queries. But there are many cases where the standard table output of a query may not be the best choice, or where further settings are desired (like the maximum number of results that should be displayed). For this purpose, inline queries have a number of other possible parameters that one can use to control their appearance in detail. The general syntax for <tt>#ask</tt> therefore is the following:\n\n <nowiki>{{</nowiki>#ask: <i>argument 1</i> | <i>argument 2</i> | &hellip; <nowiki>}}</nowiki>\n\nMost of this page explains the various arguments one may use in inline queries.','utf-8'),(182,'{{Example\n | topic=Query examples\n | description = Example that shows how to join data from two pages into one table\n | extensions= \n | keywords = table output; template query; template format\n | other links = [[Help:Join data from two pages into one table]], [[Template:PKaValueTemplate]], [[Template:PKaValueTemplateHeader]], [[Template:TableFooter]]\n}}\n== Query ==\n<pre>\n{{#ask: [[Has pKa value::+]]\n |?Has pKa value\n | format = template\n | link=none\n | template = PKaValueTemplate\n | introtemplate = PKaValueTemplateHeader\n | outrotemplate = TableFooter\n}}\n</pre>\n\n{{#ask: [[Has pKa value::+]]\n |?Has pKa value\n | format = template\n | link=none\n | template = PKaValueTemplate\n | introtemplate = PKaValueTemplateHeader\n | outrotemplate = Footer\n}}','utf-8'),(183,'{{Example\n | description = <code>#set</code> parser function supports a template parameter\n | topic=Parser examples\n | extensions= \n | keywords = set parser; template usage; #set\n | other links = \n}}\n\nStarting with [[SMW 2.2]] the [[Help:Setting values|<code>#set</code>]] parser function supports a template parameter with which it is possible to add [[Help:Inline queries|<code>#ask</code>]] queries (or similar context information) to an individual silent annotation.\n\n<pre>\n{{#set:\n |Has keyword=Set;Template usage; #set\n |+sep=;\n |template=SetToUseTemplateForAskQuery\n}}\n</pre>\n\nThe [[Template:SetToUseTemplateForAskQuery]] is used to auto-generate query links for the annotated property/value pairs.\n<pre>\n<includeonly>{{#ifexpr: {{{#}}} > 0 | &#32;&middot;&#32; }}{{#ask:\n [[{{{property}}}::{{{value}}}]]\n | limit=0\n | searchlabel={{{value}}}\n}}</includeonly>\n</pre>\n\n\n[[Category:Parserhook examples]]','utf-8'),(184,'{{Example\n | description = <code>#set</code> parser function supports a template parameter\n | topic=Parser examples\n | extensions= \n | keywords = set parser; template usage;#set; in-text annotation\n | other links = \n}}\n\n<pre>\n{{InTextAnnotationDescriptionExample\n|longtext=lorem ipsum dolor sit amet